Cell cycle time (mins) (× 102)

Fig. 1 The poor agreement between the best-fit exponential distribution (red curve) and experimentally
determined cell cycle times in NIH 3T3 mouse embryonic fibroblasts grown in vitro (grey histograms).
The rate parameter of the exponential distribution was fitted by minimising the sum of squared residuals
between the curve and the bars of the histogram.

As an illustrative example, Turner et al. (2009) present a well-mixed stochastic model of small
populations of cancer stem cells, which they use to suggest treatment strategies. Both analytical
and simulated results pertaining to the survival of the tumour are based on the assumption that
inter-division times are exponentially distributed. We demonstrate later in this paper that using the
correct cell cycle time distributions (CCTDs) could alter their results leading to different suggested
treatment strategies.
Non-Markovian simulation methods exist for events which do not have exponentially distributed
inter-event times (Boguná et al., 2014). However, these algorithms are often difficult to understand
and complex to encode since we are required to keep track of every cell individually. This presents
a potential barrier to their use and consequently a barrier to the appropriate modelling of CCTDs.

bioRxiv preprint first posted online May. 26, 2017; doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.1101/142521. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was
not peer-reviewed) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

4

Christian A. Yates et al.

Given the ubiquity of the Gillespie algorithm, it would be significantly more beneficial if we could
decompose the cell cycle into a series of exponentially distributed events which could be naturally
encoded in the framework of the Gillespie algorithm. One potential solution to this problem is the
use of phase-type distributions. These are an extremely general class of distributions constructed
by convolving or “mixing” exponential distributions. Generically, the phase-type distributions are
a result of multiple Poisson processes occurring in “phases” or stages. The sequence in which these
phases occur can itself be a stochastic process. Phase-type distributions can be used to represent
the duration of any specified biochemical process since they are dense in the field of all positivevalued distributions (Rolski et al., 1999). This means that they can be used to approximate any
positive-valued distribution, of which waiting times are a specific example. In particular, we can
model the length of the cell cycle using a general phase-type distribution.
Whilst this is potentially good news, allowing us to simulate generic waiting time distributions
using the familiar Gillespie algorithm, one of the main drawbacks with using phase-type distributions is parameter identifiability. Their generic nature means, in general, that there are many
ways to fit parameters to a given experimental data set. Fortunately, there are special cases of
phase-type distributions which may allow greater parameter identifiability whilst still accurately
representing CCTDs. One particular subclass which has been suggested to accurately represent
phases of the cell cycle (and, by closedness of the sums of these distributions, the cell cycle itself)
are the hypoexponential family of distributions (Stewart, 2009). These distributions are made up of
a series of k independent exponential distributions, each with its own rate, λi , in series. Generally,
these distributions have significantly fewer parameters than the general phase-type distribution
and are therefore more appropriate as models of the cell cycle. However, if k is large then we will
still face issues with parameter identifiability in these models.
Recently, Weber et al. (2014) have suggested that a delayed hypoexponential distribution (consisting of three delayed exponential distributions in series) could be used to appropriately represent
the cell cycle. These delayed exponential distributions represents the G1 , S and a combined G2 {M
phases of the cell cycle. Their model is an extension of the seminal stochastic cell cycle model of

bioRxiv preprint first posted online May. 26, 2017; doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.1101/142521. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was
not peer-reviewed) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

A multi-stage representation of cell proliferation as a Markov process

5

Smith and Martin (1973) who use a single delayed exponential distribution to capture the variance in the cell cycle. Delayed hypoexponential distributions representing periods of the cell cycle
have been justified by appealing to the work of Bel et al. (2009). Bel et al. (2009) showed that
the completion time for a large class of complex theoretical biochemical systems, including DNA
synthesis and repair, protein translation and molecular transport, can be well approximated by
either deterministic or exponential distributions.
In both of the cell cycle models mentioned above (Smith and Martin, 1973; Weber et al., 2014),
the delay period captures a fixed deterministic time period before which the cell can not move on
to the next stage, whilst the exponentially distributed waiting time allows for the representation
of variation in the phase times. While the model of Smith and Martin (1973) has been dismissed
as being overly simplistic, the revised model of Weber et al. (2014) comprises six parameters and
therefore suffers from parameter identifiability issues. Despite this Weber et al. (2014) were able to
analyse the steady state proportions of cells in each phase and to suggest novel ways of determining
phase and cell cycle time distributions experimentally.
In this paper we consider two special cases of the general hypoexponential distribution: the
Erlang and exponentially modified Erlang distribution which, in turn, are special cases of the
Gamma and exponentially-modified Gamma distributions. For reference their PDFs PE and PEME ,
respectively, are given below:
PE pxq 

